servings: 2
author: Mimi Morley
course: main course
---

Preheat your oven to 210°C. Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} on to boil for the potatoes and broccoli. Peel and chop the @potatoes{225} into roughly 2cm chunks and separate the @broccoli{1/2} into florets. Pick the @thyme{4} leaves from their stalks (discard the stalks). Peel the @carrot{2} and remove the top and bottom. Cut in half lengthways, then chop into batons about 1cm wide and the length of your index finger. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1} into half moons. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30}(grated).

Add the potato to your pan of boiling water. Cook for ~{10%minutes}. Then add the broccoli and cook for a further ~{5%minutes}. Drain in a #colander{} and leave to steam dry for ~{2%minutes}. Meanwhile, drizzle some @oil{} into a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the @pancetta lardons{30}. Cook for ~{4%minutes} or until crispy. Remove from the heat and set aside.

Pour the @double cream{150} into a #jug{} and add half of the thyme leaves, half the cheese and the @Dijon mustard{1/2}. Season with a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{} and mix together. Pop the potato, broccoli and pancetta into an #ovenproof dish{}. Pour over the cream mixture and top with the @panko breadcrumbs{30}, remaining cheese and another pinch of salt and black pepper. Cook on the top shelf of your oven for ~{25-30%minutes} or until brown and bubbling.

Pop the @Toulouse sausages{4} on a #baking tray{}. Cook on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{25%minutes}. At the same time, put the carrot on another baking tray. Drizzle with a little @oil{} and the @honey{7.5}. Sprinkle over the remaining thyme leaves, a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{}. Give the tray a good shake. Cook in your oven for ~{25%minutes}.

> TIP: If your oven only has two shelves, just move the carrots to the very bottom.

Add a splash of @oil{} to the frying pan you used for the pancetta (no need to wash!). Put on medium heat and add the onion. Season with @salt{}, @black pepper{} and a pinch of @?sugar{} (if you have some). Cook for ~{10%minutes}, stirring occasionally until soft. Add the @balsamic vinegar{1/2}. Cook for a further ~{10%minutes} on very low heat. When the onion is soft and caramelised, put a lid on the pan and set aside.

When your gratin is brown and bubbling, the carrots are roasted and the sausages cooked, remove them all from the oven. Serve on plates, with a spoonful of caramelised onion on the side. Delicious!